# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: factorial-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In statistics, a **factorial experiment** (also known as **full factorial experiment**) investigates how multiple factors influence a specific outcome, called the response variable.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Each factor is tested at distinct values, or levels, and the experiment includes every possible combination of these levels across all factors.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] This comprehensive approach lets researchers see not only how each factor individually affects the response, but also how the factors interact and influence each other.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Often, factorial experiments simplify things by using just two levels for each factor.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] A 2x2 factorial design, for instance, has two factors, each with two levels, leading to four unique combinations to test.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The interaction between these factors is often the most crucial finding, even when the individual factors also have an effect.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] If a **full factorial design** becomes too complex due to the sheer number of combinations, researchers can use a fractional factorial design.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] This method strategically omits some combinations (usually at least half) to make the experiment more manageable.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] These combinations of factor levels are sometimes called *runs* (of an experiment), *points* (viewing the combinations as vertices of a graph), and *cells* (arising as intersections of rows and columns).
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Factorial designs were used in the 19th century by John Bennet Lawes and Joseph Henry Gilbert of the Rothamsted Experimental Station.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Ronald Fisher argued in 1926 that "complex" designs (such as factorial designs) were more efficient than studying one factor at a time.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] A factorial design allows the effect of several factors and even interactions between them to be determined with the same number of trials as are necessary to determine any one of the effects by itself with the same degree of accuracy.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Frank Yates made significant contributions, particularly in the analysis of designs, by the Yates analysis.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The term "factorial" may not have been used in print before 1935, when Fisher used it in his book *The Design of Experiments*.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Many people examine the effect of only a single factor or variable.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The main disadvantage of the full factorial design is its sample size requirement, which grows exponentially with the number of factors or inputs considered.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Alternative strategies with improved computational efficiency include fractional factorial designs, Latin hypercube sampling, and quasi-random sampling techniques.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In his book, *Improving Almost Anything: Ideas and Essays*, statistician George Box gives many examples of the benefits of factorial experiments.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Engineers at the bearing manufacturer SKF wanted to know if changing to a less expensive "cage" design would affect bearing lifespan.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The engineers asked Christer Hellstrand, a statistician, for help in designing the experiment.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] "The results were assessed by an accelerated life test. … The runs were expensive because they needed to be made on an actual production line and the experimenters were planning to make four runs with the standard cage and four with the modified cage.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Christer asked if there were other factors they would like to test.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] They said there were, but that making added runs would exceed their budget.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Christer showed them how they could test two additional factors "for free" – without increasing the number of runs and without reducing the accuracy of their estimate of the cage effect.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In this arrangement, called a 2×2×2 factorial design, each of the three factors would be run at two levels and all the eight possible combinations included.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The various combinations can conveniently be shown as the vertices of a cube ...
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] " "In each case, the standard condition is indicated by a minus sign and the modified condition by a plus sign.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The factors changed were heat treatment, outer ring osculation, and cage design.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The numbers show the relative lengths of lives of the bearings.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] "Remembering that bearings like this one have been made for decades, it is at first surprising that it could take so long to discover so important an improvement.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The simplest factorial experiment contains two levels for each of two factors.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Suppose an engineer wishes to study the total power used by each of two different motors, A and B, running at each of two different speeds, 2000 or 3000 RPM.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The factorial experiment would consist of four experimental units: motor A at 2000 RPM, motor B at 2000 RPM, motor A at 3000 RPM, and motor B at 3000 RPM.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Each combination of a single level selected from every factor is present once.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] This experiment is an example of a 22 (or 2×2) factorial experiment, so named because it considers two levels (the base) for each of two factors (the power or superscript), or #levels#factors, producing 22=4 factorial points.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Designs can involve many independent variables.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] As a further example, the effects of three input variables can be evaluated in eight experimental conditions shown as the corners of a cube.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] This can be conducted with or without replication, depending on its intended purpose and available resources.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] It will provide the effects of the three independent variables on the dependent variable and possible interactions.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Factorial experiments are described by two things: the number of factors, and the number of levels of each factor.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] For example, a 2×3 factorial experiment has two factors, the first at 2 levels and the second at 3 levels.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Such an experiment has 2×3=6 treatment combinations or cells.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Similarly, a 2×2×3 experiment has three factors, two at 2 levels and one at 3, for a total of 12 treatment combinations.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] If every factor has *s* levels (a so-called *fixed-level* or *symmetric* design), the experiment is typically denoted by *sk*, where *k* is the number of factors.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Thus a 25 experiment has 5 factors, each at 2 levels.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Experiments that are not fixed-level are said to be *mixed-level* or *asymmetric*.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] There are various traditions to denote the levels of each factor.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] If a factor already has natural units, then those are used.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] For example, a shrimp aquaculture experiment might have factors *temperature* at 25 °C and 35 °C, *density* at 80 or 160 shrimp/40 liters, and *salinity* at 10%, 25% and 40%.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In many cases, though, the factor levels are simply categories, and the coding of levels is somewhat arbitrary.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] For example, the levels of an 6-level factor might simply be denoted 1, 2, ..., 6.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Treatment combinations are denoted by ordered pairs or, more generally, ordered tuples.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In the aquaculture experiment, the ordered triple (25, 80, 10) represents the treatment combination having the lowest level of each factor.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In a general 2×3 experiment the ordered pair (2, 1) would indicate the cell in which factor *A* is at level 2 and factor *B* at level 1.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The parentheses are often dropped, as shown in the accompanying table.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] If these values represent "low" and "high" settings of a treatment, then it is natural to have 1 represent "high", whether using 0 and 1 or −1 and 1.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] This is illustrated in the accompanying table for a 2×2 experiment.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] If the factor levels are simply categories, the correspondence might be different; for example, it is natural to represent "control" and "experimental" conditions by coding "control" as 0 if using 0 and 1, and as 1 if using 1 and −1.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] An example of the latter is given below.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] That example illustrates another use of the coding +1 and −1.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] For other fixed-level (*sk*) experiments, the values 0, 1, ..., *s*−1 are often used to denote factor levels.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] These are the values of the integers modulo *s* when *s* is prime.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The *expected response* to a given treatment combination is called a *cell mean*, usually denoted using the Greek letter μ.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] (The term *cell* is borrowed from its use in tables of data.) This notation is illustrated here for the 2 × 3 experiment.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] A *contrast in cell means* is a linear combination of cell means in which the coefficients sum to 0.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Contrasts are of interest in themselves, and are the building blocks by which main effects and interactions are defined.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] is a contrast that compares the mean responses of the treatment combinations 11 and 12.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] is said to *belong to the main effect of factor A* as it contrasts the responses to the "1" level of factor A with those for the "2" level.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The main effect of *A* is said to be *absent* if the true values of the cell means $\mu _{ij}$ make this expression equal to 0.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Since the true cell means are unobservable in principle, a statistical hypothesis test is used to assess whether this expression equals 0.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Since it is the coefficients of these contrasts that carry the essential information, they are often displayed as column vectors.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The columns of such a table are called *contrast vectors*: their components add up to 0.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Each effect is determined by both the *pattern of components* in its columns and the *number of columns*.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Similar definitions hold for interactions of more than two factors.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In the 2 × 3 example, for instance, the pattern of the *A* column follows the pattern of the levels of factor *A*, indicated by the first component of each cell.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Similarly, the pattern of the *B* columns follows the levels of factor *B* (sorting on *B* makes this easier to see).
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The **number of columns** needed to specify each effect is the *degrees of freedom* for the effect, and is an essential quantity in the analysis of variance.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The formula for more than two factors follows this pattern.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In the 2 × 3 example above, the degrees of freedom for the two main effects and the interaction — the number of columns for each — are 1, 2 and 2, respectively.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In the tables in the following examples, the entries in the "cell" column are treatment combinations: The first component of each combination is the level of factor *A*, the second for factor *B*, and the third (in the 2 × 2 × 2 example) the level of factor *C*.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The entries in each of the other columns sum to 0, so that each column is a contrast vector.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The two contrast vectors for *A* depend only on the level of factor *A*.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] This can be seen by noting that the pattern of entries in each *A* column is the same as the pattern of the first component of "cell".
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] (If necessary, sorting the table on *A* will show this.) Thus these two vectors belong to the main effect of *A*.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Similarly, the two contrast vectors for *B* depend only on the level of factor *B*, namely the second component of "cell", so they belong to the main effect of *B*.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The last four column vectors belong to the *A × B* interaction, as their entries depend on the values of both factors, and as all four columns are orthogonal to the columns for *A* and *B*.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The latter can be verified by taking dot products.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The columns for *A*, *B* and *C* represent the corresponding main effects, as the entries in each column depend only on the level of the corresponding factor.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] For example, the entries in the *B* column follow the same pattern as the middle component of "cell", as can be seen by sorting on *B*.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The columns for *AB*, *AC* and *BC* represent the corresponding two-factor interactions.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Finally, the *ABC* column represents the three-factor interaction: its entries depend on the levels of all three factors, and it is orthogonal to the other six contrast vectors.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Combined and read row-by-row, columns *A, B, C* give an alternate notation, mentioned above, for the treatment combinations (cells) in this experiment: cell 000 corresponds to +++, 001 to ++−, etc.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In columns *A* through *ABC*, the number 1 may be replaced by any constant, because the resulting columns will still be contrast vectors.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] is "the" main effect of factor *A*, a numerical quantity that can be estimated.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] For more than two factors, a 2*k* factorial experiment can usually be recursively designed from a 2*k*−1 factorial experiment by replicating the 2*k*−1 experiment, assigning the first replicate to the first (or low) level of the new factor, and the second replicate to the second (or high) level.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] This framework can be generalized to, *e.g.*, designing three replicates for three level factors, *etc*.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] A factorial experiment allows for estimation of experimental error in two ways.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The experiment can be replicated, or the sparsity-of-effects principle can often be exploited.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Replication is more common for small experiments and is a very reliable way of assessing experimental error.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] When the number of factors is large (typically more than about 5 factors, but this does vary by application), replication of the design can become operationally difficult.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In these cases, it is common to only run a single replicate of the design, and to assume that factor interactions of more than a certain order (say, between three or more factors) are negligible.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Under this assumption, estimates of such high order interactions are estimates of an exact zero, thus really an estimate of experimental error.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] When there are many factors, many experimental runs will be necessary, even without replication.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] For example, experimenting with 10 factors at two levels each produces 210=1024 combinations.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] At some point this becomes infeasible due to high cost or insufficient resources.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In this case, fractional factorial designs may be used.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] As with any statistical experiment, the experimental runs in a factorial experiment should be randomized to reduce the impact that bias could have on the experimental results.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] In practice, this can be a large operational challenge.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Factorial experiments can be used when there are more than two levels of each factor.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] However, the number of experimental runs required for three-level (or more) factorial designs will be considerably greater than for their two-level counterparts.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Factorial designs are therefore less attractive if a researcher wishes to consider more than two levels.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] A factorial experiment can be analyzed using ANOVA or regression analysis.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] To compute the main effect of a factor "A" in a 2-level experiment, subtract the average response of all experimental runs for which A was at its low (or first) level from the average response of all experimental runs for which A was at its high (or second) level.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Other useful exploratory analysis tools for factorial experiments include main effects plots, interaction plots, Pareto plots, and a normal probability plot of the estimated effects.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] When the factors are continuous, two-level factorial designs assume that the effects are linear.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] If a quadratic effect is expected for a factor, a more complicated experiment should be used, such as a central composite design.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Optimization of factors that could have quadratic effects is the primary goal of response surface methodology.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Montgomery gives the following example of analysis of a factorial experiment:.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Onwards, the minus (−) and plus (+) signs will indicate whether the factor is run at a low or high level, respectively.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The non-parallel lines in the A:C interaction plot indicate that the effect of factor A depends on the level of factor C.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] A similar results holds for the A:D interaction.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The graphs indicate that factor B has little effect on filtration rate.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The analysis of variance (ANOVA) including all 4 factors and all possible interaction terms between them yields the coefficient estimates shown in the table below.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Because there are 16 observations and 16 coefficients (intercept, main effects, and interactions), p-values cannot be calculated for this model.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The coefficient values and the graphs suggest that the important factors are A, C, and D, and the interaction terms A:C and A:D.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The coefficients for A, C, and D are all positive in the ANOVA, which would suggest running the process with all three variables set to the high value.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] However, the main effect of each variable is the average over the levels of the other variables.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The A:C interaction plot above shows that the effect of factor A depends on the level of factor C, and vice versa.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Factor A (temperature) has very little effect on filtration rate when factor C is at the + level.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] But Factor A has a large effect on filtration rate when factor C (formaldehyde) is at the − level.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The combination of A at the + level and C at the − level gives the highest filtration rate.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] This observation indicates how one-factor-at-a-time analyses can miss important interactions.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Only by varying both factors A and C at the same time could the engineer discover that the effect of factor A depends on the level of factor C.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] The best filtration rate is seen when A and D are at the high level, and C is at the low level.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] This result also satisfies the objective of reducing formaldehyde (factor C).
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Because B does not appear to be important, it can be dropped from the model.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Performing the ANOVA using factors A, C, and D, and the interaction terms A:C and A:D, gives the result shown in the following table, in which all the terms are significant (p-value < 0.05).
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Reporting guidelines are available for factorial randomized controlled trials, such as the CONSORT 2010 extension for reporting factorial trial articles and SPIRIT 2013 extension for reporting factorial trial protocols.
[src:factorial-design/factorial-experiment] Detailed explanations and examples of good reporting and conduct were provided in an explaination and elaboration paper of the CONSORT and SPIRIT extensions.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] In statistics, a **fractional factorial design** is a way to conduct experiments with fewer experimental runs than a full factorial design.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Instead of testing every single combination of factors, it tests only a carefully selected portion.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] This "fraction" of the full design is chosen to reveal the most important information about the system being studied (sparsity-of-effects principle), while significantly reducing the number of runs required.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] It is based on the idea that many tests in a full factorial design can be redundant.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] However, this reduction in runs comes at the cost of potentially more complex analysis, as some effects can become intertwined, making it impossible to isolate their individual influences.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Therefore, choosing which combinations to test in a fractional factorial design must be done carefully.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Fractional factorial design was introduced by British statistician David John Finney in 1945, extending previous work by Ronald Fisher on the full factorial experiment at Rothamsted Experimental Station.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Developed originally for agricultural applications, it has since been applied to other areas of engineering, science, and business.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Similar to a full factorial experiment, a fractional factorial experiment investigates the effects of independent variables, known as factors, on a response variable.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Each factor is investigated at different values, known as levels.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The response variable is measured using a combination of factors at different levels, and each unique combination is known as a run.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] To reduce the number of runs in comparison to a full factorial, the experiments are designed to confound different effects and interactions, so that their impacts cannot be distinguished.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] If higher-order interactions between main effects are negligible, it can be considered a reasonable method to study the main effects.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] This is the sparsity of effects principle.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Confounding is controlled by a systematic selection of runs from a full-factorial table.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Fractional designs are expressed using the notation *l*k − p, where *l* is the number of levels of each factor, *k* is the number of factors, and *p* describes the size of the fraction of the full factorial used.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Formally, p is the number of generators; relationships that determine the intentionally confounded effects that reduce the number of runs needed.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Each generator halves the number of runs required.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] A design with *p* such generators is a 1/(*lp*)=*l−p* fraction of the full factorial design.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] For example, a 25 − 2 design is 1/4 of a two-level, five-factor factorial design.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Rather than the 32 runs that would be required for the full 25 factorial experiment, this experiment requires only eight runs.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] With two generators, the number of experiments has been halved twice.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] In practice, one rarely encounters *l* > 2 levels in fractional factorial designs as the methodology to generate such designs for more than two levels is much more cumbersome.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] In cases requiring 3 levels for each factor, potential fractional designs to pursue are Latin squares, mutually orthogonal Latin squares, and Taguchi methods.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Response surface methodology can also be a much more experimentally efficient way to determine the relationship between the experimental response and factors at multiple levels, but it requires that the levels are continuous.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] In determining whether more than two levels are needed, experimenters should consider whether they expect the outcome to be nonlinear with the addition of a third level.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Another consideration is the number of factors, which can significantly change the experimental labor demand.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The levels of a factor are commonly coded as +1 for the higher level, and −1 for the lower level.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] For a three-level factor, the intermediate value is coded as 0.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] To save space, the points in a factorial experiment are often abbreviated with strings of plus and minus signs.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The strings have as many symbols as factors, and their values dictate the level of each factor: conventionally, - for the first (or low) level, and + for the second (or high) level.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The points in a two-level experiment with two factors can thus be represented as $--$ , $+-$ , $-+$ , and $++$ .
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] (1) is used to indicate that all factors are at their lowest (or first) values.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Factorial points are typically arranged in a table using Yates’ standard order: 1, a, b, ab, c, ac, bc, abc, which is created when the level of the first factor alternates with each run.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] In practice, experimenters typically rely on statistical reference books to supply the "standard" fractional factorial designs, consisting of the *principal fraction*.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The *principal fraction* is the set of treatment combinations for which the generators evaluate to + under the treatment combination algebra.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] However, in some situations, experimenters may take it upon themselves to generate their own fractional design.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] A fractional factorial experiment is generated from a full factorial experiment by choosing an *alias structure*.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The alias structure determines which effects are confounded with each other.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] For example, the five-factor 25 − 2 can be generated by using a full three-factor factorial experiment involving three factors (say *A*,*B*, and *C*) and then choosing to confound the two remaining factors *D* and *E* with interactions generated by *D* = *A***B* and *E* = *A***C*.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] These two expressions are called the *generators* of the design.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] So for example, when the experiment is run and the experimenter estimates the effects for factor *D*, what is really being estimated is a combination of the main effect of *D* and the two-factor interaction involving *A* and *B*.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] An important characteristic of a fractional design is the defining relation, which gives the set of interaction columns equal in the design matrix to a column of plus signs, denoted by *I*.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] In this case, the defining relation of the fractional design is *I* = *ABD* = *ACE* = *BCDE*.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The defining relation allows the alias pattern of the design to be determined and includes 2p words.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Notice that in this case, the interaction effects *ABD*, *ACE*, and *BCDE* cannot be studied at all.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] As the number of generators and the degree of fractionation increases, more and more effects become confounded.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The alias pattern can then be determined through multiplying by each factor column.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Thus main effect A is confounded with interaction effects BC, CE, and ABCDE.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Other main effects can be computed following a similar method.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] An important property of a fractional design is its **resolution** or ability to separate main effects and low-order interactions from one another.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Formally, if the factors are binary then the resolution of the design is the minimum word length in the defining relation excluding (*I*).
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The resolution is denoted using Roman numerals, and it increases with the number.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The 25 − 2 design above is resolution III since its defining relation is I = ABD = ACE = BCDE.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The resolution classification system described is only used for regular designs.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Regular designs have run size that equal a power of two, and only full aliasing is present.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Non-regular designs, sometimes known as Plackett-Burman designs, are designs where run size is a multiple of 4; these designs introduce partial aliasing, and generalized resolution is used as design criterion instead of the resolution described previously.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Resolution III designs can be used to construct saturated designs, where N-1 factors can be investigated in only N runs.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] These saturated designs can be used for quick screening when many factors are involved.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Montgomery gives the following example of a fractional factorial experiment.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] An engineer performed an experiment to increase the filtration rate (output) of a process to produce a chemical, and to reduce the amount of formaldehyde used in the process.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The full factorial experiment is described in the Wikipedia page Factorial experiment.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Four factors were considered: temperature (A), pressure (B), formaldehyde concentration (C), and stirring rate (D).
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The results in that example were that the main effects A, C, and D and the AC and AD interactions were significant.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The results of that example may be used to simulate a fractional factorial experiment using a half-fraction of the original 2*4* = 16 run design.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The table shows the 2*4*-*1* = 8 run half-fraction experiment design and the resulting filtration rate, extracted from the table for the full 16 run factorial experiment.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] In this fractional design, each main effect is aliased with a 3-factor interaction (e.g., A = BCD), and every 2-factor interaction is aliased with another 2-factor interaction (e.g., AB = CD).
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The aliasing relationships are shown in the table.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] This is a resolution IV design, meaning that main effects are aliased with 3-way interactions, and 2-way interactions are aliased with 2-way interactions.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The analysis of variance estimates of the effects are shown in the table below.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] From inspection of the table, there appear to be large effects due to A, C, and D.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] The coefficient for the AB interaction is quite small.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Unless the AB and CD interactions have approximately equal but opposite effects, these two interactions appear to be negligible.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] If A, C, and D have large effects, but B has little effect, then the AC and AD interactions are most likely significant.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] These conclusions are consistent with the results of the full-factorial 16-run experiment.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Because B and its interactions appear to be insignificant, B may be dropped from the model.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Dropping B results in a full factorial 2*3* design for the factors A, C, and D.
[src:factorial-design/fractional-factorial-design] Performing the anova using factors A, C, and D, and the interaction terms A:C and A:D, gives the results shown in the table, which are very similar to the results for the full factorial experiment experiment, but have the advantage of requiring only a half-fraction 8 runs rather than 16.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] In the design of experiments and analysis of variance, a **main effect** is the effect of an independent variable on a dependent variable averaged across the levels of any other independent variables.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] The term is frequently used in the context of factorial designs and regression models to distinguish main effects from interaction effects.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Relative to a factorial design, under an analysis of variance, a main effect test will test the hypotheses expected such as H0, the null hypothesis.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Running a hypothesis for a main effect will test whether there is evidence of an effect of different treatments.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] However, a main effect test is nonspecific and will not allow for a localization of specific mean pairwise comparisons (simple effects).
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] A main effect test will merely look at whether overall there is something about a particular factor that is making a difference.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] In other words, it is a test examining differences amongst the levels of a single factor (averaging over the other factor and/or factors).
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Main effects are essentially the overall effect of a factor.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] A factor averaged over all other levels of the effects of other factors is termed as main effect (also known as marginal effect).
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] The contrast of a factor between levels over all levels of other factors is the main effect.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] The difference between the marginal means of all the levels of a factor is the main effect of the response variable on that factor.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Main effects are the primary independent variables or factors tested in the experiment.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Main effect is the specific effect of a factor or independent variable regardless of other parameters in the experiment.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] In design of experiment, it is referred to as a factor but in regression analysis it is referred to as the independent variable.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] In factorial designs, thus two levels each of factor A and B in a factorial design, the main effects of two factors say A and B can be calculated.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] We use factor level 1 to denote the low level, and level 2 to denote the high level.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] The letter "a" represent the factor combination of level 2 of A and level 1 of B and "b" represents the factor combination of level 1 of A and level 2 of B.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] "ab" is the represents both factors at level 2.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Finally, 1 represents when both factors are set to level 1.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Consider a two-way factorial design in which factor A has 3 levels and factor B has 2 levels with only 1 replicate.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] There are 6 treatments with 5 degrees of freedom. in this example, we have two null hypotheses.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] The main effect for factor A can be computed with 2 degrees of freedom.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] This variation is summarized by the sum of squares denoted by the term SSA.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Likewise the variation from factor B can be computed as SSB with 1 degree of freedom.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] SSA and SSB are main-effects sums of squares.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] The two remaining degrees of freedom can be used to describe the variation that comes from the interaction between the two factors and can be denoted as SSAB.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Take a $2^{2}$ factorial design (2 levels of two factors) testing the taste ranking of fried chicken at two fast food restaurants.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Let taste testers rank the chicken from 1 to 10 (best tasting), for factor X: "spiciness" and factor Y: "crispiness." Level X1 is for "not spicy" chicken and X2 is for "spicy" chicken.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Level Y1 is for "not crispy" and level Y2 is for "crispy" chicken.
[src:factorial-design/main-effect] Suppose that five people (5 replicates) tasted all four kinds of chicken and gave a ranking of 1-10 for each.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] , each combination ( −−, −+, +−, ++) appears three – i.e. the same number of times.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] For the case of two levels (*L* = 2), Plackett and Burman used the method found in 1933 by Raymond Paley for generating orthogonal matrices whose elements are all either 1 or −1 (Hadamard matrices).
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] Paley's method could be used to find such matrices of size *N* for most *N* equal to a multiple of 4.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] In particular, it worked for all such *N* up to 100 except *N* = 92.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] If *N* is a power of 2, however, the resulting design is identical to a fractional factorial design, so Plackett–Burman designs are mostly used when *N* is a multiple of 4 but not a power of 2 (i.e.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] If one is trying to estimate less than *N* parameters (including the overall average), then one simply uses a subset of the columns of the matrix.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] For the case of more than two levels, Plackett and Burman rediscovered designs that had previously been given by Raj Chandra Bose and K.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] Kishen at the Indian Statistical Institute.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] Plackett and Burman give specifics for designs having a number of experiments equal to the number of levels *L* to some integer power, for *L* = 3, 4, 5, or 7.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] When interactions between factors are not negligible, they are often confounded in Plackett–Burman designs with the main effects, meaning that the designs do not permit one to distinguish between certain main effects and certain interactions.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] In 1993, Dennis Lin described a construction method via half-fractions of Plackett–Burman designs, using one column to take half of the rest of the columns.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] The resulting matrix, minus that column, is a "supersaturated design" for finding significant first order effects, under the assumption that few exist.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] Box–Behnken designs can be made smaller, or very large ones constructed, by replacing the fractional factorials and incomplete blocks traditionally used for plan and seed matrices, respectively, with Plackett–Burmans.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] Adding axial points allows estimating univariate cubic and quartic effects.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] By equivocating certain columns with parameters to be estimated, Plackett–Burmans can also be used to construct mixed categorical and numerical designs, with interactions or high order effects, requiring no more than 4 runs more than the number of model parameters to be estimated.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] Sort by *a-1* columns assigned to categorical variable *A* and following columns, where *A* = 1 + int(*a*·*i* /(max(*i*) + 0.00001)), *i* = row number and *a* = *A's* number of values.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] Next sort on columns assigned to any other categorical variables and following columns, repeating as needed.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] Such designs, if large, may otherwise be incomputable by standard search techniques like D-optimality.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] For example, 13 variables averaging 3 values each could have well over a million combinations to search.
[src:factorial-design/plackett-burman-design] To estimate the 105 parameters in a quadratic model of 13 variables, one must formally exclude from consideration or compute |X'X| for well over 106C102, i.e.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Traditionally, statistical methods have relied on mean-unbiased estimators of treatment effects: Under the conditions of the Gauss–Markov theorem, least squares estimators have minimum variance among all mean-unbiased linear estimators.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] The emphasis on comparisons of means also draws (limiting) comfort from the law of large numbers, according to which the sample means converge to the true mean.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Fisher's textbook on the design of experiments emphasized comparisons of treatment means.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] However, loss functions were avoided by Ronald A.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Taguchi knew statistical theory mainly from the followers of Ronald A.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Fisher, who also avoided loss functions.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Reacting to Fisher's methods in the design of experiments, Taguchi interpreted Fisher's methods as being adapted for seeking to improve the mean outcome of a process.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Indeed, Fisher's work had been largely motivated by programmes to compare agricultural yields under different treatments and blocks, and such experiments were done as part of a long-term programme to improve harvests.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] However, Taguchi realised that in much industrial production, there is a need to produce an outcome *on target*, for example, to machine a hole to a specified diameter, or to manufacture a cell to produce a given voltage.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Shewhart and others before him, that excessive variation lay at the root of poor manufactured quality and that reacting to individual items inside and outside specification was counterproductive.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] He therefore argued that quality engineering should start with an understanding of quality costs in various situations.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] In much conventional industrial engineering, the quality costs are simply represented by the number of items outside specification multiplied by the cost of rework or scrap.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] However, Taguchi insisted that manufacturers broaden their horizons to consider *cost to society*.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] These losses are externalities and are usually ignored by manufacturers, which are more interested in their private costs than social costs.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Such externalities prevent markets from operating efficiently, according to analyses of public economics.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Taguchi argued that such losses would inevitably find their way back to the originating corporation (in an effect similar to the tragedy of the commons), and that by working to minimise them, manufacturers would enhance brand reputation, win markets and generate profits.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Such losses are, of course, very small when an item is near to negligible.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Wheeler characterised the region within specification limits as where we *deny that losses exist*.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] As we diverge from nominal, losses grow until the point where *losses are too great to deny* and the specification limit is drawn.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Edwards Deming would describe them, *unknown and unknowable*, but Taguchi wanted to find a useful way of representing them statistically.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] On-target, minimum-variation (for example, a mating part in an assembly).
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] The first two cases are represented by simple monotonic loss functions.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Though many of Taguchi's concerns and conclusions are welcomed by statisticians and economists, some ideas have been especially criticized.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] For example, Taguchi's recommendation that industrial experiments maximise some *signal-to-noise ratio* (representing the magnitude of the mean of a process compared to its variation) has been criticized.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Taguchi realized that the best opportunity to eliminate variation of the final product quality is during the design of a product and its manufacturing process.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Consequently, he developed a strategy for quality engineering that can be used in both contexts.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] This is design at the conceptual level, involving creativity and innovation.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Once the concept is established, the nominal values of the various dimensions and design parameters need to be set, the detail design phase of conventional engineering.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Taguchi's radical insight was that the exact choice of values required is under-specified by the performance requirements of the system.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] In many circumstances, this allows the parameters to be chosen so as to minimize the effects on performance arising from variation in manufacture, environment and cumulative damage.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] This is sometimes called robustification.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Robust parameter designs consider controllable and uncontrollable noise variables; they seek to exploit relationships and optimize settings that minimize the effects of the noise variables.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] With a successfully completed *parameter design*, and an understanding of the effect that the various parameters have on performance, resources can be focused on reducing and controlling variation in the critical few dimensions.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Taguchi developed his experimental theories independently.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Taguchi's designs aimed to allow greater understanding of variation than did many of the traditional designs from the analysis of variance (following Fisher).
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Taguchi contended that conventional sampling is inadequate here as there is no way of obtaining a random sample of future conditions.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] In Fisher's design of experiments and analysis of variance, experiments aim to reduce the influence of nuisance factors to allow comparisons of the mean treatment-effects.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Variation becomes even more central in Taguchi's thinking.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Taguchi proposed extending each experiment with an "outer array" (possibly an orthogonal array); the "outer array" should simulate the random environment in which the product would function.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] This is an example of judgmental sampling.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Many quality specialists have been using "outer arrays".
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Later innovations in outer arrays resulted in "compounded noise." This involves combining a few noise factors to create two levels in the outer array: First, noise factors that drive output lower, and second, noise factors that drive output higher.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] "Compounded noise" simulates the extremes of noise variation but uses fewer experimental runs than would previous Taguchi designs.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Many of the orthogonal arrays that Taguchi has advocated are saturated arrays, allowing no scope for estimation of interactions.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] This is a continuing topic of controversy.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] However, this is only true for "control factors" or factors in the "inner array".
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] By combining an inner array of control factors with an outer array of "noise factors", Taguchi's approach provides "full information" on control-by-noise interactions, it is claimed.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Taguchi argues that such interactions have the greatest importance in achieving a design that is robust to noise factor variation.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] The Taguchi approach provides more complete interaction information than typical fractional factorial designs, its adherents claim.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Statisticians in response surface methodology (RSM) advocate the "sequential assembly" of designs: In the RSM approach, a screening design is followed by a "follow-up design" that resolves only the confounded interactions judged worth resolution.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] A second follow-up design may be added (time and resources allowing) to explore possible high-order univariate effects of the remaining variables, as high-order univariate effects are less likely in variables already eliminated for having no linear effect.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] With the economy of screening designs and the flexibility of follow-up designs, sequential designs have great statistical efficiency.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] The sequential designs of response surface methodology require far fewer experimental runs than would a sequence of Taguchi's designs.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] Genichi Taguchi has made valuable contributions to statistics and engineering.
[src:factorial-design/taguchi-methods] His emphasis on *loss to society*, techniques for investigating variation in experiments, and his overall strategy of system, parameter and tolerance design have been influential in improving manufactured quality worldwide.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] In statistics, a **Yates analysis** is an approach to analyzing data obtained from a designed experiment where a factorial design has been used.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Full- and fractional-factorial designs are common in designed experiments for engineering and scientific applications.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] In these designs, each factor is assigned two levels, typically called the low and high levels and referred to as "-" and "+".
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] For computational purposes the factors are scaled so that the low level is assigned a value of -1 and the high level is assigned a value of +1.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] A full factorial design contains all possible combinations of low/high levels for all the factors.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] A fractional factorial design contains a carefully chosen subset of these combinations.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The criterion for choosing the subsets is discussed in detail in the fractional factorial designs article.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Formalized by Frank Yates, a Yates analysis exploits the special structure of these designs to generate least squares estimates for factor effects for all factors and all relevant interactions.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] What is the goodness-of-fit (as measured by the residual standard deviation) for the various models?
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The mathematical details of the Yates analysis are given in chapter 10 of Box, Hunter and Hunter (1978).
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The Yates analysis is typically complemented by a number of graphical techniques such as the DOE mean plot and the DOE contour plot ("DOE" stands for "design of experiments").
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Before performing a Yates analysis, the data should be arranged in "Yates' order".
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] That is, given *k* factors, the *k*th column consists of 2(*k* - 1) minus signs (i.e., the low level of the factor) followed by 2(*k* - 1) plus signs (i.e., the high level of the factor).
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] To better understand and utilize the sign table above, one method of detailing the factors and treatment combinations is called modern notation.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The notation is a shorthand that arises from taking the subscripts of each treatment combination, making them exponents, evaluating the resulting expression and using that as the new name of the treatment combination.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Note that while the names look very much like algebraic expressions, they are simply names and no new values are assigned.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] in which it is evident that the exponents in the modern notation names are simply the subscripts of the former (note that anything raised to the zeroth power is 1 and anything raised to the first power is itself).
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Each response variable then gets assigned row-wise to the table above.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Thus the first row is for 1 , the second row is for a and so on.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The signs in each column then represent the signs each response variable should take in the calculation of the effect estimates for that factor.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Determining the Yates' order for fractional factorial designs requires knowledge of the confounding structure of the fractional factorial design.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] A Yates analysis generates the following output.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] To determine the magnitudes, the response variables are first arranged in Yates' order, as described in the aforementioned section above.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Then, terms are added and subtracted pairwise to determine the next column.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] More specifically, given the values of the response variables (as they should have been obtained from the experiment directly) in Yates' order, the first two terms are added and that sum is now the first term in the new column.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The next two terms are then added and that is the second term in the new column.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Since the terms are added pairwise, half of the new column is now filled and should be composed entirely of the pairwise sums of the data.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The second half of the column is found in an analogous manner, only the pairwise differences are taken, where the first term is subtracted from the second, the third from the fourth, and so on.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Should more columns be needed, the same process is repeated, only using the new column.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] In other words, the nth column is generated from the (n-1)th column (Berger et al. calls this process "Yatesing the data").
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] In a $2^{k}$ design, k columns will be required, and the last column is the column used to calculate the effect estimates.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] where *e* is the estimated factor effect and *se* is the standard deviation of the estimated factor effect.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] where *Xi* is the estimate of the *i*th factor or interaction effect.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] This consists of a monotonically decreasing set of residual standard deviations (indicating a better fit as the number of terms in the model increases).
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] where the constant is the overall mean of the response variable.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] This last model will have a residual standard deviation of zero.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] (Adapted from Berger et al., chapter 9) Say there is a study done where one is selling some product by mail and is trying to determine the effect of three factors (postage, product price, envelope size) on people's response rate (that is, will they buy the product).
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Each factor has two levels: for postage (labeled A), they are third-class (low) and first-class (high), for product price (labeled B) the low level is $9.95 and the high level is $12.95, and for envelope size (labeled C) the low level is #10 and the high level is 9x12.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] From the experiment, the following data are acquired.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Note that the response rate is given as a proportion of the people who answered the survey (favorably and unfavorably) for each treatment combination.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Singling out factor A (postage) for calculation for now, the overall estimate for A must take into account the interaction effects of B and C on it as well.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The total estimate is the sum of these four terms divided by four.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] where the sum has been rearranged to have all the positive terms grouped together and the negatives together for ease of viewing.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The estimates for B and C can be determined in a similar fashion.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Calculating the interaction effects is also similar, but the responses are averaged over all other effects not considered.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The full table of signs for a three-factor, two-level design is given to the right.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Both the factors (columns) and the treatment combinations (rows) are written in Yates' order.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The value of arranging the sum in Yates' order is now apparent, as only the signs need to be altered according to the table to produce the effect estimates for every treatment combination.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Observe that the columns for A, B, and C are the same as those in the design matrix in the above Yates' order section.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Observe also that the columns of the interaction effects can be produced by taking the dot product of the columns of the individual factors (i.e., multiplying the columns element-wise to produce another column of the same length).
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Note that all sums must divided by 4 to yield the actual effect estimate, as shown earlier.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] A positive value means that an increase in the factor creates an increase in the response rate, while a negative value means that that same factor increase actually produces a decrease in the response rate.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Note however that these effects have not yet been determined to be statistically significant, only that there are such effects on the response rate for each factor.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Statistical significance must be ascertained via other methods such as analysis of variance (ANOVA).
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Further reading can be found in Berger et al., chapter 9.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] In most cases of least squares fitting, the model coefficients for previously added terms change depending on what was successively added.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] For example, the *X*1 coefficient might change depending on whether or not an *X*2 term was included in the model.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] This is not the case when the design is orthogonal, as is a 23 full factorial design.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] For orthogonal designs, the estimates for the previously included terms do not change as additional terms are added.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] This means the ranked list of effect estimates simultaneously serves as the least squares coefficient estimates for progressively more complicated models.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] From the above Yates output, one can define the potential models from the Yates analysis.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] An important component of a Yates analysis is selecting the best model from the available potential models.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The above step lists all the potential models.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] From this list, we want to select the most appropriate model.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] This requires balancing the following two goals.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] That is, the model should be as simple as possible.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] In short, we want our model to include all the important factors and interactions and to omit the unimportant factors and interactions.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Note that the residual standard deviation alone is insufficient for determining the most appropriate model as it will always be decreased by adding additional factors.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Instead, seven criteria are utilized to define important factors.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] These seven criteria are not all equally important, nor will they yield identical subsets, in which case a consensus subset or a weighted consensus subset must be extracted.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] In practice, some of these criteria may not apply in all situations, and some analysts may have additional criteria.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] These criteria are given as useful guidelines.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Mosts analysts will focus on those criteria that they find most useful.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The first four criteria focus on effect sizes with three numeric criteria and one graphical criterion.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The fifth criterion focuses on averages.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] The last two criteria focus on the residual standard deviation of the model.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Once a tentative model has been selected, the error term should follow the assumptions for a univariate measurement process.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] That is, the model should be validated by analyzing the residuals.
[src:factorial-design/yates-analysis] Some analysts may prefer a more graphical presentation of the Yates results.
